article.headline: First time ever in shot clock era
article.linkText: Pistons hold Nuggets without double-digit scorer
article.story:
DENVER (AP) -- Denver's Jon Barry walked off during a timeout and hurled his gum at the scorer's table. Carmelo Anthony was right behind, head down and shoulders slumped. The Detroit Pistons can have that kind of effect on teams. Rasheed Wallace had 20 points and 10 rebounds, and the Pistons held Denver without a scorer in double figures in a 97-66 win Saturday night. "That was just embarrassing," Barry said. "Take your pick. Anything basketball-related, you can say we were bad at it." Detroit played its second straight game without leading scorer Richard Hamilton because of a broken nose, but it didn't matter in its first game this season against the reeling Nuggets. The Pistons had 22 offensive rebounds and held Denver without a field goal for 12:28 -- 0-for-19 -- during a stunning 40-5 run spanning the second and third quarters to win for the sixth time in seven games. Corliss Williamson added 14 points for Detroit, which has won six straight over the Nuggets. "It's always fun," Detroit's Ben Wallace said. "We have everybody out there sharing the basketball and things seem to come easy when you are playing like that. You have to like that." The Nuggets looked more like the team that set the league scoring futility mark last season than the one that led the Midwest Division as late as December. Denver shot 32 percent and became the first team without a player scoring in double figures since the shot clock was implemented in 1954-55. The Nuggets have lost seven of eight and are just 1½ games ahead of Utah for the final playoff spot in the Western Conference. "It's alarming," Nuggets coach Jeff Bzdelik. "Over 82 games you're going to have a lot of jewels and some bummers. This was a bummer." The Nuggets were ragged on offense and had numerous breakdowns on defense during a woeful first half. It didn't get much better to start the second. Tayshaun Prince blew by Anthony for a dunk over Nene to open the third quarter, then Ben and Rasheed Wallace scored on consecutive alley-oop dunks. Lindsey Hunter followed with a pullup jumper that put Detroit up 64-39 with 8:44 left, leading to boos from the home crowd. But the Pistons weren't done. Prince scored on a putback and had a 3-pointer from the corner, then Ben Wallace had a reverse dunk on an alley-oop to make it 71-39. Andre Miller finally broke through for the Nuggets with a leaner at 5:41, leading to sarcastic cheers from the fans. "They pretty much did what they wanted to with the ball," Miller said. Denver had trouble from the start, particularly Anthony. He seemed intent to prove that Detroit made a mistake by taking Darko Milicic instead of him with the second pick in the draft. It didn't work. Anthony, who went to Denver with the third pick, missed his first seven shots, including two that were blocked and three straight in front of the rim in a span of five seconds. He broke through at 6:29, hitting a 22-foot jumper at the shot-clock buzzer, then followed with a no-look pass to Marcus Camby for a three-point play on a two-handed dunk over Williamson. But that was about it. Anthony finished the first half 3-for-16 and took one shot the rest of the way to finish with eight points. "He didn't shoot the ball too good," Pistons coach Larry Brown said. "I've been watching that kid play, and that was not a typical Carmelo game." Milicic, who rarely plays, entered with 9:24 left in the game and drew cheers from the crowd with a jump hook over Chris Andersen. Milicic finished with four points.

Game notes
The game was plagued with technical difficulties from the start. The public address announcer called out the score throughout the first half because the scoreboards rimming the arena weren't working. The second half was delayed because the buzzer wasn't working and officials at the scorer's table wound up using an air horn the rest of the game. ... Former Denver Broncos star Terrell Davis attended the game. ... Hamilton didn't make the trip and won't play Sunday against Seattle. ... The last team without a double-figure scorer was Nov. 22, 1950, when the Fort Wayne Pistons beat the Minneapolis Lakers 19-18.
